    Thanks for the info!
    I have similar/same WMI commands as you. But the issue is, this driver for pankha bypasses the WMI Mechanism and directly writes to the EC registers, giving us complete control.

    I dumped out some of the relevant WMI bindings from the Omen Command Center logs and I am currently trying to port my logic from EC-write to WMI queries. This has resulted in success with the CPU fan only ( GPU fan stays at 0 )

    So at the moment ec-based approach still feels superior.

    I have another question for you. What is your end goal? Are you interested in:

    1. achieving full manual control over the fans, or
    2. just the ability to toggle between auto and MAX RPM modes

    If it is [1], we will need to take a look at your EC dump in linux and try to add your board to this driver's whitelist.
    Else if it is [2], you can simply patch the hp-wmi.c file from the kernel tree and compile it yourself. Then you use the usual method of:

    echo 0 | sudo tee /sys/devices/platform/hp-wmi/hwmon/*/pwm1_enable

    To run your fans on MAX RPM

    Let me know what you need help with.

    React

    Ok it looks good. Let's try to write to EC registers and see if we can control fans

    As described in the README, register 0x19 is used to control the fan speed. Currently in your dump it looks like it is 0xff which represents invalid state. Let's change that to 0x32 ( = 50, representing 50 * 100 = 5000 RPM). However doing this alone would not cause any change, that is because the register 0x15 contains 0x00. 0x00 indicates: controlled by BIOS. We need to change that to 0x01 so that it will read the fan speed from register 0x19.

    So TL;DR, set fans to 5000 RPM:

    $ printf '\x32' | sudo dd of=/sys/kernel/debug/ec/ec0/io bs=1 seek=$((0x19)) count=1 conv=notrunc

    Change mode from BIOS to USER controlled:

    $ printf '\x01' | sudo dd of=/sys/kernel/debug/ec/ec0/io bs=1 seek=$((0x15)) count=1 conv=notrunc

    And after executing the above you should feel the fans speed up.

    To return to BIOS controlled mode again, write 0x00 into register 0x15:

    $ printf '\x00' | sudo dd of=/sys/kernel/debug/ec/ec0/io bs=1 seek=$((0x15)) count=1 conv=notrunc

    Please test the above writes and let me know if the fan speed changes.

    React
